values.text: Be present and comfortable in my own skin.

children.text: This is, partly, about leaning into myself as an autistic person. If I have routines and methods to get the most crucial things done, then I don't feel so much unease. And I want that to be okay—to have those routines that I prioritize, often over others.
Exercise, food, hygiene, and even fashion especially allow me to show up intentionally as the person I *want* to be around others.

subtasks.text: This is, partly, about leaning into myself as an autistic person. If I have routines and methods to get the most crucial things done, then I don't feel so much unease. And I want that to be okay—to have those routines that I prioritize, often over others.
Exercise, food, hygiene, and even fashion especially allow me to show up intentionally as the person I *want* to be around others.

values.text: This is, partly, about leaning into myself as an autistic person. If I have routines and methods to get the most crucial things done, then I don't feel so much unease. And I want that to be okay—to have those routines that I prioritize, often over others.
Exercise, food, hygiene, and even fashion especially allow me to show up intentionally as the person I *want* to be around others.
Spend my time on things I care about, collaborating with those I choose.

children.text: Things like exercise and cooking and hygiene, which are dearly difficult for me to maintain, go on "autopilot," which means I'm not distracted by them when I'm doing stuff I love more.
But I also want to enjoy those things! And having predictability can really allow that.
Plus, these habits are about living longer—having more time to spend with those I love and that which I love doing.
Most importantly, this clears my mind. When I'm taking care of *myself* really well, I know what and who I need and don't.
